            "detailValue": "- Emergent ERCP (endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography) is indicated for acute cholangitis with suspected choledocholithiasis.\n  → Obtain well-informed consent from the patient and family, including indications, benefits, risks (aspiration pneumonia, arrhythmias/cardiovascular events, bleeding, organ perforation, biliary tract infection, post-ERCP pancreatitis, etc.), and alternative managements (conservative treatment, PTCD/PTGBD, surgical intervention, etc.).\n  → If the patient and family understand the procedure, accept the risks, and sign consent, we will proceed with ERCP.\n  → Maintain NPO status for at least 8 hours with IV fluids before ERCP.\n  → Complete evaluation, including AST, ALT, ALK-P, GGT, T-bil, D-bil, amylase, lipase, INR, aPTT, CRP, albumin, tumor markers (CA 19-9, CEA, AFP), IgG, IgG4, HBsAg, anti-HBs Ab, anti-HBc Ab, anti-HCV if not yet checked.\n  → Avoid the use of anticoagulants/antiplatelet agents if possible, and correct any coagulopathy. Inform the patient and family of the potential thromboembolic risks associated with correction.\n  → Maintain empirical antibiotic therapy and establish IV access before ERCP. Closely monitor the patient's clinical condition and laboratory results.\n  → Inform us immediately if the patient's condition worsens.\n\n  Thank you for your consultation."
